                  </persName>
            . I <rs id="t18320517-177-viclabel1035" type="occupation">keep a ham and beef shop</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320517-177-victim1447 t18320517-177-viclabel1035"></join> in <placeName id="t18320517-177-crimeloc1036">Lower Seymour-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18320517-177-crimeloc1036" type="placeName" value="Lower Seymour-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18320517-177-crimeloc1036" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320517-177-off1033 t18320517-177-crimeloc1036"></join>. On the afternoon of the 16th of May the prisoner and another lad came to the shop, and asked for two 1d. saveloys; I said I had no 1d. ones, they should have two for 2 1/2d. - the prisoner paid 1 1/2d. for one, and left the shop; I went and spoke to my wife on the stairs - I then came into the shop, and saw the prisoner behind the counter, at the end of it; I asked what he wanted- he said, "You said we should have two for 2 1/2d.," and he threw down 1d. and took a saveloy; I went to put the penny into the till, and missed the money stated - I ran after the prisoner, and brought him back to my shop; he threw something away, went down on his knees, and begged pardon; he afterwards showed me my money in a dish- there was the bag and 1l. 3s. 6d. in it; I am sure it had been in my till; I had counted it ten minutes before they came in.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320517-177-person1449">
                  JAMES 
                  WELLS
               <interp inst="t18320517-177-person1449" type="surname" value="WELLS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320517-177-person1449" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320517-177-person1449" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             (Police-constable S 30). I was called to take the prisoner - I saw a dish in the shop; I took from it this bag, with 1l. 3s. 6d. in it: I took the prisoner into the parlour, and found a saveloy on him - he went on his knees, begged the prosecutor to forgive him, and said he would do so no more.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320517-177-person1450">
                  JOSEPH 
                  FOSTER
               <interp inst="t18320517-177-person1450" type="surname" value="FOSTER"></interp>
